To extract specific text or data from a PDF file in Perl, you can use the `PDF::API2` and `Text::CSV` modules. These modules will help you read the PDF, extract the text, and then parse it for the specific data you need. Below is a script that demonstrates how to do this. This example will focus on extracting the date, author, and tabular information from a PDF.

First, ensure you have the necessary Perl modules installed. You can install them using CPAN or your system's package manager.

```bash
cpan install PDF::API2
cpan install Text::CSV
```

Here's the Perl script:

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use PDF::API2;
use Text::CSV;
use Path::Tiny;

# Specify the PDF file path
my $pdf_file = path('example.pdf')->stringify;

# Load the PDF file
my $pdf = PDF::API2->open($pdf_file);

# Initialize CSV object
my $csv = Text::CSV->new({ binary => 1, auto_diag => 1 });

# Open a file to write the extracted data
my $output_file = path('extracted_data.csv')->stringify;
open my $fh, '>', $output_file or die "Could not open file '$output_file' $!";

# Extract date and author
my ($date, $author);
for my $page ($pdf->pages->each) {
    my $text = $page->text;
    if ($text =~ /Created: (\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2})/i) {
        $date = $1;
    }
    if ($text =~ /Author: ([^ ]+)/i) {
        $author = $1;
    }
}

print $fh "Date,Author\n";
print $fh "$date,$author\n";

# Extract table information
for my $page ($pdf->pages->each) {
    my $text = $page->text;
    if ($text =~ /Table/) {
        my @rows = split /\n/, $text;
        for my $row (@rows) {
            if ($row =~ /Table/) {
                my @fields = split /\s+/, $row;
                $csv->print($fh, \@fields);
            }
        }
    }
}

close $fh;
print "Data extracted to $output_file\n";
